Let me analyze the function and propose optimizations:

1. Analysis of current implementation:
- Reads one character at a time using fgetc()
- Each character read requires a system call (inefficient)
- Grows the buffer by 1 byte at a time (can cause frequent reallocations)
- Checks for EOF on each iteration
- Simple but very inefficient for large lines or frequent calls

2. Optimization Strategy:
The selected strategy of using buffered I/O applies perfectly here because:
- The function reads line-by-line from a file
- Current implementation has high per-character overhead
- We can read larger chunks at once and scan for the terminator
- Buffer size of 4KB-32KB would be optimal (matches common page sizes)

3. Potential Optimizations:
a) Read in chunks using fread() instead of fgetc()
b) Pre-allocate larger buffer sizes to reduce reallocations
c) Use memchr() to find the terminator in the buffer
d) Keep remaining buffer between calls (would change behavior)

4. Selected Optimization:
The highest impact change would be to implement chunked reading (option a) while maintaining the exact same external behavior. This:
- Dramatically reduces system calls
- Keeps the same interface
- Preserves all existing functionality
- Is simple to implement

5. Final Optimization Idea:
Replace character-by-character reading with buffered chunk reading:
- Read chunks of 4KB at a time
- Use memchr() to find terminator in buffer
- Only process up to terminator if found
- Fall back to current behavior if fread fails

